Review:
>The Tales of Prince Anonymous
by TheHonorableAjax

The piece starts off okay. There's a stumble in the third paragraph with the honeysuckle line, where the narrator says something close to
>"Despite the smell being overwhelming, you feel like the atmosphere is suffocating you."
"Despite" indicates contradiction further along in the sentence, but there's no contradiction with feeling suffocated by an intense smell (even if it is floral).
The prose itself leans on the fatty side, which isn't to my preference but is totally fine for the medieval fiction/fantasy genre the story falls under. The world building you weave into the first chapter is restrained but tasteful and it's clear you didn't just throw shit at the wall.
What isn't tasteful is that the story features concubinage/polygamy, and that neither your description nor tags make that clear. I went in expecting a cute story about two nobles dealing with culture shock and all of the trappings and expectations of an arranged marriage. What I got was a threesome with a maidservant in Chapter 1.
This is a DNF. Next time, give your audience adequate warning for the content they're about to read.

Anonymous Mon 08 Jul 2024 04:12:32 No.67214187 Report
Quoted By:
>>67213052
>>67213052
>please give tips

Okay:
>Figure out what kind of writer you are
If you're a write-to-plan kind of guy you should lay out something, but if you're a plan-to-write thinker then you are starting with a vague idea that just comes out. You're also not forced to do one or the other, you can do both or switch.
>Don't get hung up on word count per day
Just don't. Some people write a little, some people write a lot, it's the quality that matters. Nobody wants to read a hundred thousand words of unintelligible bullshit crammed in a single paragraph. If you can only muster a thousand words, make each one count. Five hundred words a day is five thousand in ten days, but I would caution against having a very low goal.
>Daily progress, set a realistic goal
This is the major thing to remember. If you take anything away from this post it should be this and it extends to other stuff beyond writing too.
>Decide what you're writing about
Really figure out what you intend to do and why you're doing it. Every novel I've written, every short story, I had entirely different reasons for doing them. Some were for fun, some were to get it out of my head, and some were simply a way to deal with pain.
>It's okay to be slow
Don't race other authors, it will rock your shit when you stumble and fail. This is your story, not theirs.
>It's not okay to dawdle
If you're struggling with meeting your goal, be it daily or weekly, consider what you're doing that gets in the way of that.
>Don't stress yourself
If you're not doing this for pay then it isn't a job, so don't act like it is. Adhering to a schedule is one thing, but if you're not having a good time then you might want to step back and reexamine what you're doing. Don't have a good reason? Then stop.

Of course this is just my own opinions and thoughts on the matter. Whatever works for you is what you should do.
Anonymous
